But truly cared about my wellbeing and the safety of my baby. I felt seen, heard and understood. I felt cared about and for the first time since seeing that positive pregnancy test, I felt like everything was truly going to be ok. This is the support our communities need.

Planned parenthood hung up on me when I said I wanted to keep my baby. Other clinics brushed me off. I heard "we dont do prenatal care" in every aggressive and apathetic tone possible before finally finding somewhere that, not only was willing to help me,

No, not ALL CPCs are great places. Some lie. Some use deceptive tactics. Some dont have up to date information. SOME. But so many of these centers are the only thing a lot of women have. And most of these centers are like mine, truly wanting to help and be a support.
They all cried when I told them we were both fine and baby was healthy. I sent them a pic after he was born to add to their wall of other pics they've been sent by all the families they've helped.

They called back every day to check on me for a week. My insurance kicked in and I went to the hospital to get checked once the bleeding stopped. When I got out of my appointment, I had two missed calls, one from the receptionist and one from the RN, checking on me and my baby

A week later when I thought I might be miscarrying (turns out I just had really heavy implantation bleeding) I called the center. They remembered my name and my husband's.  She stayed in the phone with me while I cried because there was nothing to be done but wait.

We left with a little bag of items, including some prenatal vitamins, a pair on tiny baby socks, pacifier and tons of info on resources like WIC and resource centers in our area where we could get baby items and maternity clothes for lower cost.

She then scheduled for me to come back for a free vaginal ultrasound which my husband was welcome to come to. The 3 staff members all crowded around the screen(they were in the room with permission) and celebrated my tiny baby's strong heartbeat.

For domestic violence and other abusive situations. I saw a registered nurse who administered a pregnancy test to confirm the pregnancy. She then helped me for over an hour, walking me through filing for Medicaid and hand wrote a letter for me to send in to ensure I got coverage.

She even took the extra step to ensure I was in a safe environment and had a support system atm before booking me to come in the very next day. The paperwork I filled out when I first arrived asked many probing questions to ensure my safety and they had tons of info for resources

I had been making phone calls for hours. After being rudely interrupted and even HUNG UP ON by other clinics, I was emotionally strung out and in tears. The receptionist was SO kind. I told her what had happened and she spent 30 mins on the phone with me reassuring me.
